FIND PEAK ELEMENT

A peak element in an array is an element that is strictly greater than its adjacent elements.

You are given a 0-based indexed integer array nums. Your task is to find the index of any one peak element in the array and return it. If multiple peak elements exist, you can return the index of any one of them.

For simplicity, assume:
arr[-1] = negative infinity
arr[arr.length] = negative infinity

Your solution must run in O(log n) time complexity.

FUNCTION DESCRIPTION

Function name: findPeakElement

This function finds the index of a peak element in the array.

PARAMETERS

nums
A 0-based indexed array of integers where adjacent elements are not equal

RETURN VALUE

Return a single integer representing the index of any peak element

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ T ≤ 1000
1 ≤ nums.length ≤ 1000
-2^31 ≤ nums[i] ≤ 2^31 - 1
nums[i] ≠ nums[i+1] for all valid indices
Time complexity must be O(log n)

INPUT FORMAT

The first line contains an integer T, the number of test cases

For each test case:
The first line contains an integer N, the size of the array
The second line contains N space-separated integers representing the array

OUTPUT FORMAT

For each test case, print a single integer — the index of a peak element

SAMPLE INPUT

2
5
5 10 7 3 8
5
2 4 3 6 1

SAMPLE OUTPUT

1
3

EXPLANATION

In the first test case, element 10 at index 1 is a peak because it is greater than both its neighbors (5 and 7).


class Solution {
    public int findPeakElement(int[] nums) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = nums.length - 1;

        while (left < right) {
            int mid =(left + right ) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1]) {
                // Peak is in the left half (including mid)
                right = mid;
            } else {
                // Peak is in the right half
                left = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return left;  // Index of the peak element
    }
}

In the second test case element 6 at index 3 is a peak as 6 > 3 and 6 > 1.
